  <!-- About Section -->
<div class="w3-main" style="margin-left:50px">
  <div class="w3-container w3-padding-32" id="about">
    <h1 class="w3-border-light-grey w3-padding-16">about</h1>
   	<h3>Old Irish</h3>
	<h5>is the oldest attested Goidelic language. The oldest surviving texts are the oldest Ogham inscriptions and glosses in Latin manuscripts (see <a href="#introduction"><b>introduction</b></a>).
	The language has a rich consonant inventory with fricatives alternating in a systematic fashion with plosives (see <a href="#sounds"><b>sounds</b></a>).
	The language is famous for its massive allomorphy, especially in the verbal system, and its word-initial mutations (see <a href="#words"><b>words</b></a>).
	Old Irish is a VSO language with a complex system of relative clause formation. It makes broad use of so-called emphatic particles to mark various discourse functions (see <a href="#structures"><b>structures</b></a>).
	</h5><br>

	<h3>Lecturers</h3>
		<h4><a href="https://www.uu.nl/staff/AMGriffith/Research%20output", target="_blank">Aaron Griffith</a></h4>
		<p class="w3-opacity">University of Utrecht</p>
		<h4><a href="https://www.maynoothuniversity.ie/people/david-stifter#main-content", target="_blank">David Stifter</a></h4>
		<p class="w3-opacity">Maynooth University</p>
	
  </div>

